16 (m) Disclosure of Utilization Review Requirements. – All of the following apply to an
17 insurer's responsibility to disclose any utilization review procedures:
18 (1) Coverage and member handbook. – In the certificate of coverage and member
19 handbook provided to covered persons, an insurer shall include a clear and
20 comprehensive description of its utilization review procedures, including the
21 procedures for appealing noncertifications and a statement of the rights and
22 responsibilities of covered persons, including the voluntary nature of the
23 appeal process, with respect to those procedures. An insurer shall also include
24 in the certificate of coverage and the member handbook information about the
25 availability of assistance from the Department's Health Insurance Smart NC,
26 including the telephone number and address of the Program. program.
27 (2) Prospective materials. – An insurer shall include a summary of its utilization
28 review procedures in materials intended for prospective covered persons.
29 (3) Membership cards. – An insurer shall print on its membership cards a toll-free
30 telephone number to call for utilization review purposes.
31 (4) Website. – An insurer shall make any current prior authorization requirements
32 and restrictions readily accessible on its website.
33 (m1) Changes to Prior Authorization. – If an insurer intends either to implement a new
34 prior authorization review requirement or restriction or to amend an existing requirement or
35 restriction, then the new or amended requirement shall not be in effect unless and until the
36 insurer's website has been updated to reflect the new or amended requirement or restriction. A
37 claim shall not be denied for failure to obtain a prior authorization if the prior authorization
38 requirement or amended requirement was not in effect on the date of service of the claim.
39 …
40 (n1) Prior Authorization Determination Validity. – All of the following apply to the length
41 of time an approved prior authorization shall remain valid under certain circumstances:
42 (1) If a covered person enrolls in a new health benefit plan offered by the same
43 insurer under which the prior authorization was approved, then the previously
44 approved prior authorization remains valid for the initial 90 days of coverage
45 under the new heath benefit plan. This section does not require coverage of a
46 service if it is not a covered service under the new health benefit plan.
47 (2) If a healthcare service, other than for in-patient care, requires prior
48 authorization and is for the treatment of a covered person's chronic condition,
49 then the prior authorization shall remain valid for no less than six months from
50 the date the healthcare provider receives notification of the prior authorization
51 approval.
